'''Delbert Rice Jr.''' (October 27, 1922 &ndash; January 26, 1983) was an [[United States|American]] [[Professional baseball|professional]] [[baseball]] player, [[coach (baseball)|coach]] and [[manager (baseball)|manager]].<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/ricede01.shtml |title=Del Rice at Baseball Reference |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> He played for 17 seasons as a [[catcher]] in [[Major League Baseball]] from {{By|1945}} to {{By|1961}}, most notably for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. Although Rice was a relatively weak hitter, he sustained a lengthy career in the major leagues due to his valuable defensive abilities.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''">{{cite book |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=8DIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA45&dq=del+rice+baseball+digest&cd=1#v=onepage&q=del%20rice%20baseball%20digest&f=false |title=Rice-Card's Daily Dish |author=Veech, Ellis |publisher=|date=August 1952 |work=Baseball Digest |accessdate=15 October 2011 }}</ref>

==Athletic career==
A native of [[Portsmouth, Ohio]], Rice attended [[Portsmouth High School (Ohio)|Portsmouth High School]] where he starred in [[American football|football]], [[basketball]] and [[Track and field|track]] as well as baseball.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/> He was contracted as an amateur [[free agent]] by the St. Louis Cardinals in [[1941 St. Louis Cardinals season|1941]].<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/> Although Rice received his induction notice into the military in {{By|1943}}, he was turned down because of a physical disqualification.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/> After playing in the [[Minor league baseball|minor leagues]] for four seasons, he made his major league debut with the Cardinals on May 2, [[1945 St. Louis Cardinals season|1945]] at the age of 22.<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/> Shortly after the season began, the Cardinals sold their star catcher, [[Walker Cooper]] to the [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]], leaving Rice to share catching duties with [[Ken O'Dea]].<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/> The veteran O'Dea, who had played with [[Baseball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] catcher [[Gabby Hartnett]] in Chicago, gave Rice tips and advice on catching.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/> Rice posted a .261 [[batting average]] in 83 games as the Cardinals finished in second place, three games behind the [[1945 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]].<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/ricede01.shtml |title=1945 National League Team Statistics and Standings |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref> 

Although he served as a backup catcher to [[Joe Garagiola, Sr.|Joe Garagiola]] in [[1946 St. Louis Cardinals season|1946]], he regularly played whenever [[Harry Brecheen]] pitched.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/> The Cardinals ended the season tied for first place with the [[1946 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]] and the two teams met in the [[1946 National League tie-breaker series]].<ref name="1946 National League Team Statistics and Standings">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1946.shtml |title=1946 National League Team Statistics and Standings |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref> It was the first playoff [[tiebreaker]] in Major League Baseball history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=3617483|title=Tiebreaker Playoff Results|work=[[ESPN.com]]|date=September 30, 2008|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> The Cardinals won the first two games of the best-of-three game series to capture the National League pennant.<ref name="1946 National League Team Statistics and Standings"/> In the [[1946 World Series]] against the [[1946 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]], Rice caught all three of Brecheen's victories, as the Cardinals defeated the Red Sox in seven games.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1946_WS.shtml |title=1946 World Series |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> He was also the hitting standout in Game 2, with a single, a double and a walk, scoring two runs in the Cardinals' 3-0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Del Rice May Become Series Ugly Duckling |agency=Associated Press |work=The Calgary Herald |page=16 |date=9 October 1946 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jyhkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mXsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=7232,1069844&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref>

In [[1947 St. Louis Cardinals season|1947]], Rice caught the majority of the team's games and guided the Cardinals' pitching staff to the lowest team [[earned run average]] and the most [[strikeout]]s in the National League, as the Cardinals finished in second place to the [[1947 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Dodgers]].<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1947.shtml#teams_standard_pitching::22 |title=1947 National League Team Statistics and Standings |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> His pitch-calling skills were made evident once again in [[1949 St. Louis Cardinals season|1949]], leading the Cardinals' pitching staff to the lowest team earned run average in the league, as the Cardinals once again finished in second place, one game behind the [[1949 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1949.shtml#teams_standard_pitching::7 |title=1949 National League Team Statistics and Standings |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> 

Rice had his best season in [[1952 St. Louis Cardinals season|1952]], posting a .259 batting average along with 11 [[home run]]s and a career-high 65 [[runs batted in]].<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/> He also led [[National League]] catchers in games played, [[putout]]s, [[Assist (baseball)|assists]] and in baserunners [[caught stealing]].<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/> The following season, Rice was named as a reserve player for the National League team in the [[1953 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1953 All-Star Game]], although an injury kept him from participating in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NLS/NLS195307140.shtml |title=1953 All-Star Game |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Injured Crandall, Rice to Miss All-Star Game |agency=Associated Press |work=The Milwaukee Sentinel |page=2 |date=9 July 1953 |accessdate=16 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nXIxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0A8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3965,691620&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> Rice was injured during a game against the Dodgers on June 7, [[1954 St. Louis Cardinals season|1954]] when [[Roy Campanella]] stole home and spiked Rice's leg.<ref>{{cite news |title=Campanella Sparking Dodgers In New Winning Streak, Clip 10 Games In Row; Giants Maintain Pace, Beat Braves |agency=United Press International |work=Greensburg Daily Tribune |page=14 |date=8 June 1954 |accessdate=16 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QbdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1jsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1288,4412021&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> While he was sidelined with the injury, his replacement, [[Bill Sarni]] hit for a .300 average for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=sarnibi01&t=b&year=1954 |title=1954 Bill Sarni Batting Log |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref>

In the middle of the [[1955 Milwaukee Braves season|1955]] season, the 32 year old Rice was traded to the Milwaukee Braves, who were in need of a backup catcher for their perennial All-Star, [[Del Crandall]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Search For Reserve Catcher Ends-Braves Get Del Rice |agency= |work=The Milwaukee Sentinel |page=4 |date=4 June 1955 |accessdate=16 February 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SG1QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=chAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4424,5672822&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> He became [[pitcher]] [[Bob Buhl]]'s personal catcher, as Buhl didn't like having Crandall calling his pitches.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yjIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&dq=del+rice+baseball+digest&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=How N.L. Teams Shape Up For 1957 |author=Dexter, Charles |publisher=|date=April 1957 |work=Baseball Digest |accessdate=16 October 2011 }}</ref> In [[1956 Milwaukee Braves season|1956]], Rice helped Buhl to an 18-8 record as the Braves held first place with two games left in the season before the team faltered and finished the season one game behind the [[1956 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Dodgers]].<ref name="Bob Buhl statistics">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/buhlbo01.shtml |title=Bob Buhl statistics |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MLN/1956-schedule-scores.shtml |title=1956 Milwaukee Braves Schedule, Box Scores and Splits |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> 

In the [[1957 Milwaukee Braves season|1957]] season, Buhl again won 18 games and posted a 2.74 earned run average with Rice as his catcher, as the Braves won the National League pennant.<ref name="Bob Buhl statistics"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MLN/1957-schedule-scores.shtml |title=1957 Milwaukee Braves Schedule, Box Scores and Splits |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> Rice became a member of his second world championship winning team when the Braves defeated the [[1957 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] in the [[1957 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1957_WS.shtml |title=1957 World Series |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref> 

The Braves won the National League pennant for a second consecutive year in [[1958 Milwaukee Braves season|1958]], but lost a rematch with the [[1958 New York Yankees season|Yankees]] in the [[1958 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1958_WS.shtml |title=1958 World Series |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> In June [[1959 Milwaukee Braves season|1959]], Rice suffered a broken leg in a collision at home plate with [[Willie Mays]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Del Rice Out For 6 Weeks |agency=Associated Press |work=Ottawa Citizen |page= |date=2 June 1959 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XB0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=d-QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1588,486880&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> He missed more than two months of the season and was used sparingly upon his return.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=ricede01&t=b&year=1959 |title=1959 Del Rice Batting Log |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> He played in only a handful of games before he was given a coaching position to make room on the roster for another player.<ref name="Milwaukee Coaches Quit">{{cite news |title=Milwaukee Coaches Quit |agency=United Press International |work=Schenectady Gazette |page=32 |date=1 October 1959 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RPEqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yokFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4411,171404&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> The Braves then released him at the end of the season.<ref name="Milwaukee Coaches Quit"/> 

Rice played for the Chicago Cubs in [[1960 Chicago Cubs season|1960]], but was released in June when the Cubs acquired catcher [[Jim Hegan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cubs Sign Ex-Brave Rice |agency=Associated Press |work=The Milwaukee Sentinel |page=11 |date=5 November 1959 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nHVQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UxAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1911,2372348&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cubs Sign Jim Hegan |agency=Associated Press |work=The Miami News |page=2 |date=28 May 1960 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=w1oyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=g-kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2046,6289754&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> One of the 18 games Rice caught as a Cub was [[Don Cardwell]]'s [[no-hitter]] on May 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHN/CHN196005152.shtml |title=May 15, 1960 Cardinals-Cubs box score |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref> He was then re-signed with the Cardinals, but only appeared in one game before being selected off waivers by the Baltimore Orioles in September.<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/> After appearing in only one game for the Orioles, he was released in October.<ref>{{cite news |title=Orioles Release Veteran Pair |agency=Associated Press |work=Spokane Daily Chronicle |page=1 |date=14 October 1960 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QwBYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MPcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1686,3499513&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref>

Rice was the first player ever to sign with the Los Angeles Angels.<ref>''The Baseball Guide,'' 1972 edition. St. Louis: The Sporting News, p. 313</ref> He played in 30 games during their inaugural [[1961 Los Angeles Angels season|1961]] campaign and was released as a player at the end of the season, but was retained within the organization.<ref>{{cite news |title=Angels Give Trio Releases |agency=Associated Press |work=Eugene Register-Guard |page= |date=12 October 1961 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TRlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9OIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2442,2216475&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> He played in his final major league game on August 31, 1961 at the age of 39.<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/>

==Career statistics==
In a seventeen-year major league career, Rice played in 1,309 [[Games played|games]], accumulating 908 [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] in 3,826 [[at bats]] for a .237 career batting average along with 79 home runs, 441 runs batted in and an [[on base percentage]] of .312.<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/> He ended his career with a .987 [[fielding percentage]].<ref name="Del Rice at Baseball Reference"/> Rice was known for his strong defensive skills, leading National League catchers in fielding percentage in {{By|1948}} and {{By|1949}}, and tying for the lead in [[double play]]s in 1949, {{By|1950}} and {{By|1951}}.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/><ref>{{cite book |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=LSsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA86&dq=july+2001+fielding+leaders+baseball+digest&cd=4#v=onepage&q=july%202001%20fielding%20leaders%20baseball%20digest&f=false |title=Fielding Leaders |author= |publisher=|date=July 2001 |work=Baseball Digest |accessdate=16 October 2011 }}</ref>

Rice also had a career in the [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]], playing four seasons for the [[Rochester Royals]] from 1946 until 1950, when [[Fred Saigh]], the Cardinals owner, asked him to concentrate on baseball.<ref name="''Rice-Card's Daily Dish''"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsecyclopedia.com/nba/rochester/rochroyals.html |title=Rochester Royals |publisher=sportsecyclopedia.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref>

==Coaching and managing career==
Rice was a longtime member of the Angels' organization. After retiring as a player, he was retained as their first base coach from [[1962 Los Angeles Angels season|1962]] to [[1966 California Angels season|1966]]. He spent the [[1967 Cleveland Indians season|1967]] season as a coach for the [[Cleveland Indians]], but then returned to the Angels as a [[Minor league baseball|minor league]] manager and had success at the AAA level. He was named Minor League Manager of the Year for [[1971 in baseball|1971]] by [[The Sporting News]] after leading the [[Salt Lake City Bees]] to a divisional title in the [[Pacific Coast League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=rice--001del#standard_managing |title=Del Rice Minor League manager statistics |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref><ref name="Del Rice, a Former Manager And Baseball Player, Is Dead">{{cite news |title=Del Rice, a Former Manager And Baseball Player, Is Dead |agency=United Press International |work=The New York Times |page= |date=28 January 1983 |accessdate=16 February 2011 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1983/01/28/obituaries/del-rice-a-former-manager-and-baseball-player-is-dead.html}}</ref>

Rice was rewarded with a promotion to manager of the [[1972 California Angels season|1972]] Angels, but after one season and a 75-80 (.484) fifth-place finish, he was replaced by [[Bobby Winkles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/managers/ricede01.shtml |title=Del Rice Major League manager statistics |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Angels bounce Del Rice, name ex-college coach |agency=Associated Press |work=The Montreal Gazette |page=27 |date=12 October 1972 |accessdate=16 February 2011 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=shMyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7KEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3970,2908841&dq=del+rice&hl=en}}</ref> He remained with the club, however, as a [[scout (sports)|scout]].

Rice died of cancer while attending a benefit dinner in his honor of in [[Garden Grove, California]], on January 26, {{By|1983}} at the age of 60.<ref name="Del Rice, a Former Manager And Baseball Player, Is Dead"/> 

